1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,420
Let's dive into gradient descent and optimizers.

2
00:00:02,420 --> 00:00:06,750
Let's find out how a neural network finds a good set of parameters.

3
00:00:06,750 --> 00:00:11,270
So, the essence of training a neural network is really just about finding a good set of parameters.

4
00:00:11,270 --> 00:00:14,070
In the last video, we introduced the concept of activation functions.

5
00:00:14,070 --> 00:00:15,410
By introducing non-linearity,

6
00:00:15,410 --> 00:00:18,600
This gives neural networks the ability to approximate any function.

7
00:00:18,600 --> 00:00:21,980
But having that ability doesn't mean you have the answer just yet.

8
00:00:21,980 --> 00:00:24,990
a model with hundreds of millions of parameters,

9
00:00:24,990 --> 00:00:26,390
But to actually make it do something useful,

10
00:00:26,390 --> 00:00:28,970
you first have to figure out the value for each of these hundreds of millions of parameters.

11
00:00:28,970 --> 00:00:31,049
But what should those values actually be?

12
00:00:31,489 --> 00:00:32,369
So, what about gradient descent?

13
00:00:32,369 --> 00:00:34,220
And that's exactly what's going to help us solve this problem.

14
00:00:34,220 --> 00:00:36,680
So, let's first take a look at the process of training a neural network.

15
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:38,660
Let's get a sense of where gradient descent fits into this process.

16
00:00:38,660 --> 00:00:39,860
so that we can better understand it.

17
00:00:39,860 --> 00:00:41,810
So, let's get into what we're going to cover next.

18
00:00:41,810 --> 00:00:44,250
So, first, we need to initialize the parameters.

19
00:00:44,250 --> 00:00:47,349
This can be done either randomly or using a tool for parameter initialization.

20
00:00:47,349 --> 00:00:48,549
So, once we have these parameters,

21
00:00:48,549 --> 00:00:52,870
Then, we use these parameters to perform forward propagation on our training data.

22
00:00:52,870 --> 00:00:55,130
to calculate a value and make a prediction.

23
00:00:55,130 --> 00:01:00,170
And we measure this prediction using something called a loss function.

24
00:01:00,170 --> 00:01:04,810
What's the difference between the value we predicted and the actual label from the data?

25
00:01:04,810 --> 00:01:06,010
With this difference,

26
00:01:06,010 --> 00:01:07,530
and we call this the loss.

27
00:01:07,530 --> 00:01:08,870
So, with this loss value,

28
00:01:08,870 --> 00:01:10,530
we can start backpropagation.

29
00:01:10,530 --> 00:01:11,970
This involves calculating the derivative for each layer.

30
00:01:11,970 --> 00:01:14,560
And the vector composed of these calculated values is what we call the gradient.

31
00:01:14,560 --> 00:01:15,700
So, once we have this,

32
00:01:15,700 --> 00:01:20,480
we can then use this method of gradient descent to update our parameters.

33
00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:23,090
This brings the parameters a little closer to their true values.

34
00:01:23,090 --> 00:01:25,410
So, what does it mean to get closer to the true value?

35
00:01:25,410 --> 00:01:28,450
Basically, it's just about making some fine-tuning adjustments to its parameters.

36
00:01:28,450 --> 00:01:29,570
So, after this fine-tuning,

37
00:01:29,570 --> 00:01:31,030
And we repeat this process.

38
00:01:31,030 --> 00:01:33,670
and then we keep performing forward propagation with the new parameters.

39
00:01:33,670 --> 00:01:34,430
calculate the loss,

40
00:01:34,430 --> 00:01:35,870
and backpropagate to update them.

41
00:01:35,870 --> 00:01:37,170
And we just keep repeating this cycle.

42
00:01:37,170 --> 00:01:39,419
until the loss is close to zero.

43
00:01:39,419 --> 00:01:41,459
Or, we've reached the maximum number of training epochs.

44
00:01:41,459 --> 00:01:42,640
and then we stop.

45
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:45,900
Alright, so training is essentially a minimization problem.

46
00:01:45,900 --> 00:01:47,160
So, what are we trying to minimize?

47
00:01:47,160 --> 00:01:50,680
In other words, it's about minimizing the loss function.

48
00:01:50,680 --> 00:01:53,210
And the corresponding theta is just a collection of all our parameters.

49
00:01:53,210 --> 00:01:57,070
So, we use the loss function to measure how far off our predictions are from the actual values, right?

50
00:01:57,070 --> 00:01:58,950
The smaller that difference is,

51
00:01:58,950 --> 00:02:01,570
the more accurate our parameters are.

52
00:02:01,570 --> 00:02:04,250
Sounds a lot like a math problem from high school, doesn't it?

53
00:02:04,250 --> 00:02:05,870
You take the derivative and set it equal to zero.

54
00:02:05,870 --> 00:02:06,950
and then just solve for it.

55
00:02:06,950 --> 00:02:09,770
But modern large models can easily have tens of billions of parameters.

56
00:02:09,770 --> 00:02:10,720
hundreds of billions of parameters.

57
00:02:10,720 --> 00:02:13,460
So, we'd end up with a system of equations that has tens or even hundreds of billions of variables.

58
00:02:13,460 --> 00:02:15,000
It has no analytical solution.

59
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:16,160
Since we can't solve it directly,

60
00:02:16,160 --> 00:02:17,800
There's no way to solve it in a single step.

61
00:02:17,800 --> 00:02:19,360
So, we'll just have to calculate it step by step.

62
00:02:19,360 --> 00:02:21,030
Letting it get a little closer each time.

63
00:02:21,030 --> 00:02:22,350
the loss gets smaller and smaller.

64
00:02:22,350 --> 00:02:26,850
And gradually, the set of parameters we land on can be considered the optimal solution.

65
00:02:26,850 --> 00:02:28,430
And that's gradient descent.

66
00:02:28,430 --> 00:02:29,810
So, what's the intuition behind gradient descent?

67
00:02:29,810 --> 00:02:33,170
And this is probably the most common example you'll see in all sorts of tutorials online.

68
00:02:33,170 --> 00:02:34,590
It's like trying to get down a mountain with your eyes closed.

69
00:02:34,590 --> 00:02:36,670
Picture yourself on a mountain.

70
00:02:36,670 --> 00:02:38,230
So, how do I get to the valley?

71
00:02:38,230 --> 00:02:39,950
So, if your eyes are blindfolded,

72
00:02:39,950 --> 00:02:42,140
I wouldn't know which way to go.

73
00:02:42,140 --> 00:02:44,320
The only way I can tell is by feeling the slope with my feet.

74
00:02:44,320 --> 00:02:45,460
I'll take a small step forward.

75
00:02:45,460 --> 00:02:49,860
to see if I'm currently going uphill or downhill.

76
00:02:49,860 --> 00:02:50,880
I'll just take another step forward.

77
00:02:50,880 --> 00:02:51,460
What if I'm going uphill?

78
00:02:51,460 --> 00:02:53,569
I'll just head in the opposite direction.

79
00:02:53,569 --> 00:02:54,689
I can, I can stick my foot out, right?

80
00:02:54,689 --> 00:02:55,569
I keep testing the ground.

81
00:02:55,569 --> 00:02:57,309
to see which way is the steepest.

82
00:02:57,309 --> 00:03:01,310
Basically, I want to take the steepest path in the opposite direction.

83
00:03:01,310 --> 00:03:02,950
And we just keep repeating this cycle.

84
00:03:02,950 --> 00:03:03,990
We take it one small step at a time, feeling our way down.

85
00:03:03,990 --> 00:03:06,800
And gradually, we'll find our way down the mountain.

86
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:10,320
In fact, this process is very similar to gradient descent.

87
00:03:10,320 --> 00:03:12,080
So, during the gradient descent process,

88
00:03:12,080 --> 00:03:13,540
We have to keep using the derivative.

89
00:03:13,540 --> 00:03:15,800
So, let's do a quick recap for everyone.

90
00:03:15,800 --> 00:03:19,180
So, the derivative is basically the instantaneous rate of change of a function.

91
00:03:19,180 --> 00:03:22,520
Let's take the simplest example: a parabola, f(x) equals x squared.

92
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:25,769
Its derivative is 2X, and its value will change depending on where you are on the curve.

93
00:03:25,769 --> 00:03:28,889
In fact, the tangent line of the derivative has a specific direction.

94
00:03:28,889 --> 00:03:29,409
So, as we can see,

95
00:03:29,409 --> 00:03:30,249
At the point where x equals three,

96
00:03:30,249 --> 00:03:31,160
the derivative is six.

97
00:03:31,160 --> 00:03:32,160
So, what does that actually mean?

98
00:03:32,160 --> 00:03:33,860
So it's a tangent line pointing to the left, right?

99
00:03:33,860 --> 00:03:35,800
Basically, the further you move to the left on the X-axis,

100
00:03:35,800 --> 00:03:37,120
the larger the Y-value will be.

101
00:03:37,120 --> 00:03:38,470
If you take a small step,

102
00:03:38,470 --> 00:03:39,890
Let's say you move by 0.01.

103
00:03:39,890 --> 00:03:41,830
So, what would the corresponding Y value be greater than?

104
00:03:41,830 --> 00:03:42,610
Is it six?

105
00:03:42,610 --> 00:03:44,970
it will increase by 0.06.

106
00:03:44,970 --> 00:03:47,610
So, for example, when it's equal to two,

107
00:03:47,610 --> 00:03:48,670
When X equals two,

108
00:03:48,670 --> 00:03:49,770
So the slope is actually four.

109
00:03:49,770 --> 00:03:51,530
So, what that means is, you take a small step to the right.

110
00:03:51,530 --> 00:03:53,460
So, is it pointing to the right?

111
00:03:53,460 --> 00:03:54,440
if you take a small step to the right,

112
00:03:54,440 --> 00:03:56,020
So, let's say it moves by 0.01.

113
00:03:56,020 --> 00:03:59,870
the value of the function will increase by 0.04.

114
00:03:59,870 --> 00:04:01,490
And when it's equal to zero,

115
00:04:01,490 --> 00:04:03,150
Now, this is something you all really need to pay attention to.

116
00:04:03,150 --> 00:04:04,650
We'll get to point N in a bit.

117
00:04:04,650 --> 00:04:08,980
Or, to put it another way, when we talk about gradients vanishing, this is what we're referring to.

118
00:04:08,980 --> 00:04:11,940
So, when the gradient we calculate, which is the slope, gets close to zero...

119
00:04:11,940 --> 00:04:13,300
So why is that a disaster?

120
00:04:13,300 --> 00:04:17,040
Actually, this concept applies regardless of whether the calculated value is positive or negative.

121
00:04:17,040 --> 00:04:18,500
We know how to make the update.

122
00:04:18,500 --> 00:04:19,780
Should we go left or right?

123
00:04:19,780 --> 00:04:21,440
whether it will make it larger or smaller.

124
00:04:21,440 --> 00:04:24,060
So basically, you just move in the direction of the derivative.

125
00:04:24,060 --> 00:04:24,880
it will get larger.

126
00:04:24,880 --> 00:04:26,260
But what if we go in the opposite direction of the derivative?

127
00:04:26,260 --> 00:04:27,640
it will get smaller.

128
00:04:27,640 --> 00:04:29,080
But what if it's equal to zero?

129
00:04:29,080 --> 00:04:29,800
So what does that mean?

130
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:30,280
move to the left,

131
00:04:30,280 --> 00:04:30,820
or to the right.

132
00:04:30,820 --> 00:04:32,200
the function won't change at all.

133
00:04:32,200 --> 00:04:34,200
So, what happens when the gradient is equal to zero?

134
00:04:34,200 --> 00:04:36,720
we won't know which way the gradient should go next.

135
00:04:36,720 --> 00:04:39,420
This situation can make our calculations extremely difficult.

136
00:04:39,420 --> 00:04:41,270
So, when we're performing gradient descent,

137
00:04:41,270 --> 00:04:43,110
We need to avoid a derivative value of zero.

138
00:04:43,110 --> 00:04:45,290
So, what if we extend this from two dimensions to multiple dimensions?

139
00:04:45,290 --> 00:04:49,180
So basically, this happens when we have multiple variables in our loss function.

140
00:04:49,180 --> 00:04:54,110
So, we have X1 through XN. What we'll do is take the partial derivative with respect to each of these variables.

141
00:04:54,110 --> 00:04:55,410
Together, they form a vector.

142
00:04:55,410 --> 00:04:57,370
And this vector is what we call the gradient.

143
00:04:57,370 --> 00:04:58,550
It has a direction.

144
00:04:58,550 --> 00:05:02,580
It represents the direction of the steepest ascent at the current point, theta.

145
00:05:02,580 --> 00:05:03,780
So, that's what a gradient is.

146
00:05:03,780 --> 00:05:06,760
So, what if we want to reduce the overall loss?

147
00:05:06,760 --> 00:05:08,280
We just take the negative of it.

148
00:05:08,280 --> 00:05:10,040
and take a small step in the opposite direction.

149
00:05:10,040 --> 00:05:11,900
This is the direction of the steepest descent.

150
00:05:11,900 --> 00:05:14,620
So, what exactly is the workflow for gradient descent?

151
00:05:14,620 --> 00:05:17,400
For example, let's say we're at the seventh step.

152
00:05:17,400 --> 00:05:20,020
So, we know we have a matrix of parameters.

153
00:05:20,020 --> 00:05:21,540
We just want to make it smaller.

154
00:05:21,540 --> 00:05:23,240
to make the overall loss a little smaller.

155
00:05:23,240 --> 00:05:25,640
So, I'll subtract this... this is the gradient, right?

156
00:05:25,640 --> 00:05:26,780
multiplied by a learning rate.

157
00:05:26,780 --> 00:05:31,020
We'll have it take a tiny step forward, in the opposite direction of the gradient.

158
00:05:31,020 --> 00:05:32,280
We can't take too big of a step.

159
00:05:32,280 --> 00:05:33,700
This prevents us from going in the wrong direction.

160
00:05:33,700 --> 00:05:36,480
By taking small steps, I can gradually get closer to the solution.

161
00:05:37,560 --> 00:05:38,860
Alright, let's look at a quick example.

162
00:05:38,860 --> 00:05:42,180
For example, when X, or X0, is equal to four.

163
00:05:42,180 --> 00:05:44,160
This is actually the point we're trying to find.

164
00:05:44,160 --> 00:05:45,380
So, this is actually the point where the loss is at.

165
00:05:45,380 --> 00:05:47,620
But of course, what we're trying to do is get it to zero, right?

166
00:05:47,620 --> 00:05:49,649
When we get to the point where the loss is zero,

167
00:05:49,649 --> 00:05:51,249
So, how do we get it to zero, step by step?

168
00:05:51,249 --> 00:05:53,200
For example, let's say the learning rate is 0.1.

169
00:05:53,200 --> 00:05:54,980
So, when the value is four,

170
00:05:54,980 --> 00:05:57,720
So, let's see, the value we get is 16.

171
00:05:57,720 --> 00:05:59,240
So when we plug in four,

172
00:05:59,240 --> 00:06:01,049
And the derivative of that is eight.

173
00:06:01,049 --> 00:06:04,469
So each time, we have it subtract 8 times 0.1.

174
00:06:04,469 --> 00:06:05,369
So that's 0.8.

175
00:06:05,369 --> 00:06:08,870
So, that's it for this step. Now, we move on to the next one.

176
00:06:08,870 --> 00:06:11,490
So in this step, we're going to multiply its value by 0.1 again.

177
00:06:11,490 --> 00:06:13,320
And as you keep doing this, you'll notice that...

178
00:06:13,320 --> 00:06:15,720
And as a result, our Y value will get smaller and smaller.

179
00:06:15,720 --> 00:06:16,280
getting smaller and smaller.

180
00:06:16,280 --> 00:06:18,100
Until, well, this is actually the loss value, right?

181
00:06:18,100 --> 00:06:19,220
until it approaches zero.

182
00:06:19,220 --> 00:06:20,460
getting infinitely close to zero.

183
00:06:20,460 --> 00:06:24,299
and we can consider the current parameters to be good enough.

184
00:06:24,299 --> 00:06:25,859
So, in this simple example,

185
00:06:25,859 --> 00:06:27,479
We can also make three observations here.

186
00:06:27,479 --> 00:06:29,199
The slower it moves.

187
00:06:29,199 --> 00:06:30,080
Right?

188
00:06:30,080 --> 00:06:32,200
See how big the steps are at the beginning.

189
00:06:32,200 --> 00:06:35,280
In other words, the change in our loss is actually getting smaller and smaller.

190
00:06:35,280 --> 00:06:37,600
This means the change in our loss is getting smaller and smaller.

191
00:06:37,600 --> 00:06:40,680
So, you can think of it as having a built-in brake.

192
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:42,990
Another thing is that it's monotonically decreasing.

193
00:06:42,990 --> 00:06:45,200
Each step gets us closer to zero than the last.

194
00:06:45,200 --> 00:06:46,400
And it just keeps getting closer and closer.

195
00:06:46,400 --> 00:06:48,320
But it's very difficult to actually reach zero.

196
00:06:48,320 --> 00:06:50,700
So, the point isn't to get an exact value of zero.

197
00:06:50,700 --> 00:06:53,150
Getting close enough is good enough.

198
00:06:53,150 --> 00:06:54,910
In a real neural network,

199
00:06:54,910 --> 00:06:56,390
And the process is actually the same.

200
00:06:56,390 --> 00:06:58,030
Of course, let's just briefly touch on this.

201
00:06:58,030 --> 00:07:01,900
Now, the learning rate is actually a very sensitive hyperparameter throughout the entire training process.

202
00:07:01,900 --> 00:07:03,360
So, why do we pick 0.1?

203
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:05,880
or 0.01 is a common choice in practice.

204
00:07:05,880 --> 00:07:08,760
The problem with this is that if the learning rate is too large, it can cause the model to oscillate.

205
00:07:08,760 --> 00:07:09,680
or even diverge.

206
00:07:09,680 --> 00:07:11,840
If it's too small, the learning process will be too slow.

207
00:07:11,840 --> 00:07:16,230
So, we'll also cover how to tune the learning rate in a separate video later on.

208
00:07:16,230 --> 00:07:17,830
Of course, in the upcoming sections,

209
00:07:17,830 --> 00:07:22,160
Now, some of our optimizers actually handle the learning rate adjustment themselves, based on the principles of gradient descent.

210
00:07:22,160 --> 00:07:23,000
And that's pretty much how it works.

211
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:24,600
So, with the knowledge we have so far,

212
00:07:24,600 --> 00:07:26,840
and you can implement a neural network on your own.

213
00:07:26,840 --> 00:07:29,489
But when it comes to actually training a neural network,

214
00:07:29,489 --> 00:07:30,769
But we generally don't do it this way.

215
00:07:30,769 --> 00:07:33,329
Because, in reality, this approach is a bit inefficient.

216
00:07:33,329 --> 00:07:35,810
Now, this formula might look incredibly simple,

217
00:07:35,810 --> 00:07:37,590
But in a real-world scenario,

218
00:07:37,590 --> 00:07:40,120
The first question is, how many samples' gradients are we using?

219
00:07:40,120 --> 00:07:41,720
You're only training on a single sample each time.

220
00:07:41,720 --> 00:07:43,060
and that gives us a gradient.

221
00:07:43,060 --> 00:07:44,480
So, how many parameters are you updating at once?

222
00:07:44,480 --> 00:07:46,420
So, should you use all the samples?

223
00:07:46,420 --> 00:07:47,620
And then, where do we go from there?

224
00:07:47,620 --> 00:07:49,480
Imagine you're in a narrow, elongated valley.

225
00:07:49,480 --> 00:07:50,420
So, what about your next step?

226
00:07:50,420 --> 00:07:52,180
it might seem like the right move for now is to go down.

227
00:07:52,180 --> 00:07:53,420
But in reality, overall,

228
00:07:53,420 --> 00:07:55,440
This isn't because you're heading in the optimal direction.

229
00:07:55,440 --> 00:07:58,320
If you're in a canyon like this, you can get to this side in just one step.

230
00:07:58,320 --> 00:08:00,020
You'll find you still have to take a step in this direction.

231
00:08:00,020 --> 00:08:01,060
and then you have to move back this way.

232
00:08:01,060 --> 00:08:01,880
It keeps oscillating back and forth.

233
00:08:01,880 --> 00:08:03,630
So, how can we avoid this?

234
00:08:03,630 --> 00:08:05,750
And another thing is, how should the learning rate be distributed?

235
00:08:05,750 --> 00:08:07,930
Should it automatically adjust, and so on.

236
00:08:07,930 --> 00:08:09,280
So, there are all sorts of issues that come up.

237
00:08:09,280 --> 00:08:10,960
So, the optimizers we're going to talk about next...

238
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:14,400
essentially, they are here to help us solve these very problems.

239
00:08:14,400 --> 00:08:17,630
to make the gradient change in the most optimal way in real-time.

240
00:08:17,630 --> 00:08:21,150
First, let's start with the most basic form, which is the principle we just discussed.

241
00:08:21,150 --> 00:08:22,850
And this is what we call a 'batch'.

242
00:08:22,850 --> 00:08:23,930
gradient descent.

243
00:08:23,930 --> 00:08:25,410
And 'batch' just means a batch of data, right?

244
00:08:25,410 --> 00:08:27,070
We use the entire dataset every single time.

245
00:08:27,070 --> 00:08:28,380
So, after I've done the calculation,

246
00:08:28,380 --> 00:08:30,980
and that means we've trained on the entire dataset.

247
00:08:30,980 --> 00:08:32,659
Now, doing it this way actually has its benefits.

248
00:08:32,659 --> 00:08:34,299
So, I just take the average of it, right?

249
00:08:34,299 --> 00:08:36,179
So, we just use the average of its gradients.

250
00:08:36,179 --> 00:08:39,000
Actually, this all started way back in 1847.

251
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:42,520
The French mathematician Cauchy, uh, while he was studying the orbits of comets,

252
00:08:42,520 --> 00:08:44,090
And that's basically how he did it.

253
00:08:44,090 --> 00:08:46,570
So basically, what do you do when there's no analytical solution?

254
00:08:46,570 --> 00:08:47,690
You just get closer and closer, step by step.

255
00:08:47,690 --> 00:08:51,460
This was actually a very, very advanced idea for its time.

256
00:08:51,460 --> 00:08:53,660
So, when we want to update the parameters in gradient descent,

257
00:08:53,660 --> 00:08:55,980
the model has to go through the entire dataset to complete one training cycle.

258
00:08:55,980 --> 00:08:58,600
and then perform an update using the averaged gradient.

259
00:08:58,600 --> 00:09:02,660
So, by now, you've probably figured out its pros and cons.

260
00:09:02,660 --> 00:09:06,740
So, the advantage is that we're actually using all of the data.

261
00:09:06,740 --> 00:09:07,550
virtually

262
00:09:07,550 --> 00:09:10,410
So, you could say the training process is a very accurate reflection of the real data.

263
00:09:10,410 --> 00:09:13,370
But the downside is, the training cost is just too high.

264
00:09:13,370 --> 00:09:16,220
You have to run through the entire dataset just to calculate a single gradient.

265
00:09:16,220 --> 00:09:17,460
It just takes way too long.

266
00:09:17,460 --> 00:09:18,940
Plus, it lacks randomness.

267
00:09:18,940 --> 00:09:21,180
it gets stuck in a saddle point or a region with a small gradient.

268
00:09:21,180 --> 00:09:22,540
so there's no noise to jolt it out of there.

269
00:09:22,540 --> 00:09:23,560
and that helps it get out of there.

270
00:09:23,560 --> 00:09:26,220
This is actually what I was explaining to you all earlier when we were talking about functions.

271
00:09:26,220 --> 00:09:28,300
If it reaches a point where the calculation results in zero,

272
00:09:28,300 --> 00:09:30,160
when it's obviously not at the lowest point yet.

273
00:09:30,160 --> 00:09:32,390
but when its gradient is about to hit zero,

274
00:09:32,390 --> 00:09:34,710
So, in a situation like this, we're pretty much talking about gradient descent, right?

275
00:09:34,710 --> 00:09:36,810
we multiply the learning rate by the gradient,

276
00:09:36,810 --> 00:09:38,210
And no matter how small the learning rate is,

277
00:09:38,210 --> 00:09:39,330
no matter what the learning rate is,

278
00:09:39,330 --> 00:09:40,390
When the gradient is zero,

279
00:09:40,390 --> 00:09:41,690
What you're subtracting is the value of the parameter.

280
00:09:41,690 --> 00:09:42,940
But the amount you're subtracting is always zero.

281
00:09:42,940 --> 00:09:45,060
If it's in a region that's completely flat,

282
00:09:45,060 --> 00:09:45,960
So when it gets to a place like this,

283
00:09:45,960 --> 00:09:47,480
it won't continue to go down any further.

284
00:09:47,480 --> 00:09:49,870
it won't be able to find the lowest point, relatively speaking.

285
00:09:49,870 --> 00:09:51,790
and it'll just get stuck in certain spots.

286
00:09:51,790 --> 00:09:53,410
It thinks it has found a low point,

287
00:09:53,410 --> 00:09:55,430
In reality, this is just a local minimum.

288
00:09:55,430 --> 00:09:57,040
but not the lowest point overall.

289
00:09:57,040 --> 00:09:58,440
This approach just won't work.

290
00:09:59,440 --> 00:10:02,140
And this is basically the formula we saw at the very beginning.

291
00:10:02,140 --> 00:10:03,990
So, what happens when the gradient is zero?

292
00:10:03,990 --> 00:10:07,430
In fact, the parameter itself is the same at time T+1 as it was at time T.

293
00:10:07,430 --> 00:10:08,680
it stops changing.

294
00:10:08,680 --> 00:10:10,400
So, how do we avoid this?

295
00:10:10,400 --> 00:10:13,320
So, to address this, we introduce Stochastic Gradient Descent.

296
00:10:13,320 --> 00:10:17,430
Each time, I just use a single random sample to update the gradient.

297
00:10:17,430 --> 00:10:20,670
And actually, this approach is grounded in some real-world principles.

298
00:10:20,670 --> 00:10:22,089
I just have to keep doing this over and over again.

299
00:10:22,089 --> 00:10:23,029
and keep on adjusting it,

300
00:10:23,029 --> 00:10:25,149
and in the long run, it will converge to the true solution.

301
00:10:25,149 --> 00:10:26,209
So, here's the general formula.

302
00:10:26,209 --> 00:10:30,180
So, you can see that this part here, what was it in the previous formula?

303
00:10:30,180 --> 00:10:32,660
Now, you don't need to get too bogged down in the details of this formula.

304
00:10:32,660 --> 00:10:34,180
Just having a general idea of the principle is enough.

305
00:10:34,180 --> 00:10:36,500
So, after we've calculated all the losses,

306
00:10:36,500 --> 00:10:37,600
and take the average.

307
00:10:37,600 --> 00:10:39,020
So, what's the situation now?

308
00:10:39,020 --> 00:10:41,280
We just randomly pick one from the numbers one to N.

309
00:10:41,280 --> 00:10:43,140
And we just use the one we picked.

310
00:10:43,140 --> 00:10:45,880
And its pros and cons are also very clear.

311
00:10:45,880 --> 00:10:48,040
The upside is that it's incredibly efficient.

312
00:10:48,040 --> 00:10:48,720
Right?

313
00:10:48,720 --> 00:10:50,100
And since you're just randomly picking one,

314
00:10:50,100 --> 00:10:51,520
It's inherently noisy.

315
00:10:51,520 --> 00:10:54,280
It might even help us during the training process,

316
00:10:54,280 --> 00:10:56,120
Let's break out of the saddle point.

317
00:10:56,120 --> 00:10:57,920
But the downside is that it's just too inaccurate.

318
00:10:57,920 --> 00:10:58,500
The thing is,

319
00:10:58,500 --> 00:11:02,350
So, during the training process, you'll find that the loss fluctuates wildly.

320
00:11:02,350 --> 00:11:05,370
So, it all comes down to how lucky you get with your random sampling.

321
00:11:05,370 --> 00:11:07,589
And on top of that, if you're just unlucky,

322
00:11:07,589 --> 00:11:09,009
and you happen to pick an outlier.

323
00:11:09,009 --> 00:11:10,589
it's actually an outlier.

324
00:11:10,589 --> 00:11:12,920
this outlier data will take our gradient and...

325
00:11:12,920 --> 00:11:15,760
and pulls our entire set of parameters in a really weird direction.

326
00:11:15,760 --> 00:11:19,020
We'd have to train it many times just to pull it back.

327
00:11:19,020 --> 00:11:22,210
But sometimes, this can actually make things less efficient.

328
00:11:22,210 --> 00:11:25,500
But in reality, this approach actually makes a lot of sense.

329
00:11:25,500 --> 00:11:27,300
It's just that every time, we only draw one sample.

330
00:11:27,300 --> 00:11:29,220
But it did come with some pretty significant issues.

331
00:11:29,220 --> 00:11:31,920
But it did inspire the optimizers that came after it.

332
00:11:31,920 --> 00:11:33,900
So, what's the optimizer that came after that?

333
00:11:33,900 --> 00:11:36,200
Mini-batch Stochastic Gradient Descent.

334
00:11:36,200 --> 00:11:39,560
So, for mini-batch... well, the first one we have is batch gradient descent.

335
00:11:39,560 --> 00:11:41,140
The second one is Stochastic Gradient Descent.

336
00:11:41,140 --> 00:11:43,180
And the third one? It's a combination of the two.

337
00:11:43,180 --> 00:11:46,420
So, it's stochastic, but we're just taking a small, random batch.

338
00:11:46,420 --> 00:11:47,760
Doing it all at once is too aggressive,

339
00:11:47,760 --> 00:11:48,900
But using the entire batch is way too slow.

340
00:11:48,900 --> 00:11:50,000
So, I'll just find a middle ground.

341
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:54,820
So, each time, we randomly sample a batch—say, 32 or 128 samples.

342
00:11:54,820 --> 00:11:56,490
So, we just take a portion each time.

343
00:11:56,490 --> 00:12:00,290
This way, it combines the benefits of both approaches,

344
00:12:00,290 --> 00:12:01,390
and the drawbacks were balanced out.

345
00:12:01,390 --> 00:12:03,610
And the computation is also significantly faster.

346
00:12:03,610 --> 00:12:04,130
Makes sense, right?

347
00:12:04,130 --> 00:12:06,030
Plus, the oscillations aren't as severe anymore.

348
00:12:06,030 --> 00:12:07,810
And at the same time, because it's also stochastic,

349
00:12:07,810 --> 00:12:09,880
So, it still maintains a certain degree of randomness.

350
00:12:09,880 --> 00:12:12,960
So, as you can see, it's actually incredibly useful in many ways.

351
00:12:12,960 --> 00:12:15,160
So, nowadays, a lot of the time...

352
00:12:15,160 --> 00:12:17,780
So, when we talk about SGD, or Stochastic Gradient Descent,

353
00:12:17,780 --> 00:12:20,380
In practice, we're no longer talking about just randomly picking a single sample.

354
00:12:20,380 --> 00:12:22,620
So, even if we don't have 'mini-batch' in front of it,

355
00:12:22,620 --> 00:12:23,320
Mini-batch.

356
00:12:23,320 --> 00:12:26,380
This also refers to mini-batch stochastic gradient descent.

357
00:12:26,380 --> 00:12:31,320
It strikes a remarkably good balance between statistical efficiency and computational efficiency.

358
00:12:31,320 --> 00:12:33,040
So, when we talk about SGD,

359
00:12:33,040 --> 00:12:36,100
By default, the 'S' in SGD actually refers to mini-batch SGD.

360
00:12:36,100 --> 00:12:39,060
Now, even though mini-batch SGD is already quite good,

361
00:12:39,060 --> 00:12:43,280
But of course, brilliant minds were still constantly researching and pushing the boundaries in this field.

362
00:12:43,280 --> 00:12:44,200
In 1964,

363
00:12:44,200 --> 00:12:47,420
So, when Soviet mathematicians were studying the convergence speed of iterative methods,

364
00:12:47,420 --> 00:12:49,230
and proposed a method called Momentum.

365
00:12:49,230 --> 00:12:53,010
The core idea is that you shouldn't just look at the gradient of the current step.

366
00:12:53,010 --> 00:12:57,330
Instead, you also need to factor in the momentum from the past few steps.

367
00:12:57,330 --> 00:12:58,510
When the directions are aligned,

368
00:12:58,510 --> 00:13:00,170
the update gets continuously reinforced.

369
00:13:00,170 --> 00:13:03,900
This way, those oscillating updates are gradually neutralized.

370
00:13:03,900 --> 00:13:06,839
Let's take a look at an example of an iron ball rolling down a mountain.

371
00:13:06,839 --> 00:13:09,399
Now, the plain vanilla gradient descent we started with...

372
00:13:09,399 --> 00:13:11,419
So, for each small section it goes down,

373
00:13:11,419 --> 00:13:13,819
it has to stop and calculate the current gradient.

374
00:13:13,819 --> 00:13:15,310
and then take another small step.

375
00:13:15,310 --> 00:13:16,790
So it stops right here.

376
00:13:16,790 --> 00:13:17,790
and it finds that the gradient is zero.

377
00:13:17,790 --> 00:13:19,250
Because this area is flat, right?

378
00:13:19,250 --> 00:13:21,089
It might just stop moving downwards.

379
00:13:21,089 --> 00:13:22,409
It can't be optimized any further.

380
00:13:22,409 --> 00:13:24,660
It figures that going left would also be zero.

381
00:13:24,660 --> 00:13:25,800
and going right is also zero.

382
00:13:25,800 --> 00:13:26,320
Alright then.

383
00:13:26,320 --> 00:13:27,660
This must be the lowest point then.

384
00:13:27,660 --> 00:13:28,240
I'm not moving.

385
00:13:28,240 --> 00:13:29,940
But in reality, if you take just one more step forward...

386
00:13:29,940 --> 00:13:31,200
there's actually a lower point.

387
00:13:31,200 --> 00:13:33,680
But in the real, physical world,

388
00:13:33,680 --> 00:13:34,960
Imagine a small ball rolling down a mountain.

389
00:13:34,960 --> 00:13:36,100
But that's not actually how it works.

390
00:13:36,100 --> 00:13:37,830
until it reaches a flat area.

391
00:13:37,830 --> 00:13:39,270
It will keep moving forward.

392
00:13:39,270 --> 00:13:39,830
Why is that?

393
00:13:39,830 --> 00:13:41,940
Because as it was going down the slope earlier,

394
00:13:41,940 --> 00:13:43,360
It has a certain amount of inertia.

395
00:13:43,360 --> 00:13:44,480
When it encounters some small

396
00:13:44,480 --> 00:13:46,380
or even over some small bumps,

397
00:13:46,380 --> 00:13:48,560
so it won't get stuck oscillating back and forth here.

398
00:13:48,560 --> 00:13:50,950
and it'll use that inertia to break right through.

399
00:13:50,950 --> 00:13:52,310
It won't veer off to the left,

400
00:13:52,310 --> 00:13:53,150
and then to the right.

401
00:13:53,150 --> 00:13:54,310
Because it has this momentum,

402
00:13:54,310 --> 00:13:55,620
This will keep it moving straight forward.

403
00:13:55,620 --> 00:13:56,800
and it just pushes right through.

404
00:13:56,800 --> 00:14:01,090
So basically, what this means is that gradient descent doesn't just consider your current gradient.

405
00:14:01,090 --> 00:14:03,010
but also the gradients from previous steps.

406
00:14:03,010 --> 00:14:04,510
If they're in the same direction,

407
00:14:04,510 --> 00:14:05,910
I need to factor that in as well.

408
00:14:05,910 --> 00:14:07,470
This way, it keeps pushing forward.

409
00:14:07,470 --> 00:14:08,829
so the updates are much faster.

410
00:14:08,829 --> 00:14:11,129
So, the formula for this would basically look something like this.

411
00:14:11,129 --> 00:14:12,409
So, what are the benefits of this?

412
00:14:12,409 --> 00:14:17,230
If the gradient directions in several consecutive steps of gradient descent are all very similar,

413
00:14:21,300 --> 00:14:23,600
In fact, it also dampens this kind of left-right oscillation.

414
00:14:23,600 --> 00:14:24,180
So, why is that?

415
00:14:24,180 --> 00:14:25,300
Because it'll go left for a bit,

416
00:14:25,300 --> 00:14:25,900
and then to the right,

417
00:14:25,900 --> 00:14:27,920
But, because you're adding in the historical information,

418
00:14:27,920 --> 00:14:29,490
the leftward and rightward movements will cancel each other out.

419
00:14:29,490 --> 00:14:32,070
In reality, it will form a straight line going downwards like this.

420
00:14:32,070 --> 00:14:34,220
For this kind of narrow, elongated valley,

421
00:14:34,220 --> 00:14:35,740
So, if it actually has momentum,

422
00:14:35,740 --> 00:14:37,260
the updates will be incredibly fast.

423
00:14:37,260 --> 00:14:38,740
And, like we just mentioned,

424
00:14:38,740 --> 00:14:40,550
It also makes it easier to get past some saddle points.

425
00:14:40,550 --> 00:14:42,070
or some flat regions.

426
00:14:42,070 --> 00:14:44,390
or some small, local minima.

427
00:14:44,390 --> 00:14:47,290
Even if the instantaneous speed at that moment is close to zero,

428
00:14:47,290 --> 00:14:48,890
But because I have that momentum built up from before,

429
00:14:48,890 --> 00:14:49,980
I can still power through.

430
00:14:49,980 --> 00:14:52,020
And that's the benefit of using momentum.

431
00:14:53,100 --> 00:14:55,220
But, of course, this inertia is a double-edged sword.

432
00:14:55,220 --> 00:14:56,320
But it might also overshoot.

433
00:14:56,320 --> 00:14:58,580
It just keeps going right past it because of that inertia.

434
00:14:58,580 --> 00:15:02,020
This can also cause it to oscillate around the optimal point.

435
00:15:02,020 --> 00:15:03,420
But that's still acceptable.

436
00:15:03,420 --> 00:15:05,700
Plus, it introduces an additional hyperparameter.

437
00:15:05,700 --> 00:15:09,919
Now, to be fair, any hyperparameter is going to be somewhat sensitive.

438
00:15:09,919 --> 00:15:11,399
Values that are too small or too large just won't work well.

439
00:15:11,399 --> 00:15:13,119
Now, in most practical applications,

440
00:15:13,119 --> 00:15:15,690
And 0.9 is a pretty good number to go with.

441
00:15:15,690 --> 00:15:20,610
So, that's why in almost all subsequent Stochastic Gradient Descent training sessions,

442
00:15:20,610 --> 00:15:22,190
it will come with some momentum by default.

443
00:15:27,440 --> 00:15:30,220
And by default, it also passes a momentum value to us, which is set to...

444
00:15:30,220 --> 00:15:31,660
So basically, this is what everyone is using now.

445
00:15:31,660 --> 00:15:33,500
And for all subsequent large-scale training,

446
00:15:33,500 --> 00:15:36,660
The core idea is mini-batch SGD plus momentum.

447
00:15:36,660 --> 00:15:38,900
Okay, sounds like we've reached the grand finale, right?

448
00:15:38,900 --> 00:15:39,540
That's good enough, right?

449
00:15:39,540 --> 00:15:40,180
Right?

450
00:15:40,180 --> 00:15:42,520
But, there's always a bigger fish.

451
00:15:42,520 --> 00:15:44,820
And then, in 2011,

452
00:15:44,820 --> 00:15:46,240
But then, some researchers started to notice something.

453
00:15:46,240 --> 00:15:47,880
You see, you have different parameters.

454
00:15:47,880 --> 00:15:49,280
and they actually represent different features.

455
00:15:49,280 --> 00:15:52,460
So you're updating all of them with the exact same learning rate.

456
00:15:52,460 --> 00:15:53,500
all set to 0.1.

457
00:15:53,500 --> 00:15:55,620
Doesn't that seem a bit too simple and crude?

458
00:15:55,620 --> 00:16:00,010
For example, in NLP, which is, you know, Natural Language Processing...

459
00:16:00,010 --> 00:16:05,250
We know that the word 'the' appears with a very high frequency in any given text.

460
00:16:05,250 --> 00:16:06,210
So, during training,

461
00:16:06,210 --> 00:16:08,490
Each batch will have its corresponding parameters.

462
00:16:08,490 --> 00:16:09,590
the gradient will be very large.

463
00:16:09,590 --> 00:16:11,590
This makes the updates actually quite thorough.

464
00:16:11,590 --> 00:16:13,110
But for a word like this, you might not even recognize it.

465
00:16:13,110 --> 00:16:13,370
so the gradient will be huge,

466
00:16:13,370 --> 00:16:15,170
In fact, its frequency of occurrence is extremely low.

467
00:16:15,170 --> 00:16:18,330
It only shows up a handful of times during the entire training process.

468
00:16:18,330 --> 00:16:19,720
the gradient will be extremely small.

469
00:16:19,720 --> 00:16:22,480
So, what if we use the same learning rate for low-frequency words?

470
00:16:22,480 --> 00:16:23,780
It's pretty much impossible to train.

471
00:16:23,780 --> 00:16:26,660
Because its gradient is almost always zero.

472
00:16:26,660 --> 00:16:29,320
Only when it does appear will there be some minor changes.

473
00:16:29,320 --> 00:16:31,320
The update frequency is just way too low.

474
00:16:31,320 --> 00:16:36,220
So, the idea is to have an adaptive way to adjust the effective learning rate for this parameter.

475
00:16:36,220 --> 00:16:39,800
In other words, each parameter maintains its own learning rate independently.

476
00:16:39,800 --> 00:16:41,140
It's not shared with any other parameters.

477
00:16:41,140 --> 00:16:42,740
So I keep track of it myself, right?

478
00:16:42,740 --> 00:16:44,860
In this case, my own frequency of updates is relatively low.

479
00:16:44,860 --> 00:16:46,780
So, I'll just set the learning rate to be relatively large.

480
00:16:46,780 --> 00:16:48,420
so I can take a big step each time.

481
00:16:48,420 --> 00:16:50,240
I'm updating my parameters more frequently.

482
00:16:50,240 --> 00:16:51,920
So, I'll just set the learning rate to be pretty small.

483
00:16:51,920 --> 00:16:53,160
taking just one small step at a time.

484
00:16:53,160 --> 00:16:54,890
This is to prevent it from overshooting.

485
00:16:54,890 --> 00:16:57,710
So, what is this? It's an adaptive gradient.

486
00:16:57,710 --> 00:16:59,410
So, the formula for it looks something like this.

487
00:16:59,410 --> 00:17:03,460
In other words, it adds the square of the gradient from each step.

488
00:17:03,460 --> 00:17:06,780
And this small value we're adding here is to prevent the denominator from being zero.

489
00:17:06,780 --> 00:17:07,980
and then divide that by the learning rate.

490
00:17:07,980 --> 00:17:10,360
Basically, it's taking its past gradients into account.

491
00:17:10,360 --> 00:17:13,880
Of course, when we're updating the parameters really frequently,

492
00:17:13,880 --> 00:17:15,300
the gradient will be larger.

493
00:17:15,300 --> 00:17:17,120
So, we'll end up with a larger gradient.

494
00:17:17,120 --> 00:17:18,680
This way, the learning rate becomes smaller.

495
00:17:18,680 --> 00:17:19,180
Right?

496
00:17:19,180 --> 00:17:20,200
Because the denominator gets bigger, right?

497
00:17:20,200 --> 00:17:22,000
So, when our gradient is relatively small,

498
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:23,860
So, when the updates aren't happening very often,

499
00:17:23,860 --> 00:17:25,500
In that case, the denominator would be smaller.

500
00:17:25,500 --> 00:17:26,560
the learning rate will increase.

501
00:17:26,560 --> 00:17:28,120
This lets it update more quickly.

502
00:17:28,120 --> 00:17:30,500
So, this is essentially what we call an adaptive learning rate.

503
00:17:31,070 --> 00:17:33,690
And this, in turn, influenced a whole lot of what came after.

504
00:17:33,930 --> 00:17:35,930
But it does have its drawbacks.

505
00:17:35,930 --> 00:17:37,330
Now, this might sound great,

506
00:17:37,330 --> 00:17:40,840
The biggest problem is that the learning rate monotonically decays to zero.

507
00:17:40,840 --> 00:17:43,200
And why is that? Well, let's take a look at the formula.

508
00:17:43,200 --> 00:17:44,460
This value is always positive.

509
00:17:46,320 --> 00:17:49,560
This way, your learning rate will eventually be driven towards zero.

510
00:17:49,560 --> 00:17:51,200
And that's actually not a good thing.

511
00:17:51,200 --> 00:17:53,120
And that, right there, is its biggest problem.

512
00:17:53,120 --> 00:17:54,840
But it does have some advantages, though.

513
00:17:54,840 --> 00:17:56,960
Basically, it means you don't have to manually tune the learning rate anymore.

514
00:17:56,960 --> 00:17:59,840
And its adaptive nature also makes it particularly well-suited for sparse data.

515
00:17:59,840 --> 00:18:01,480
Because it can adjust itself, right?

516
00:18:01,480 --> 00:18:03,520
But its major problem is, what if the training isn't even finished yet?

517
00:18:03,520 --> 00:18:04,440
and the training just grinds to a halt.

518
00:18:04,440 --> 00:18:07,100
Gradually, the gradient itself will just... you know, the learning rate gets...

519
00:18:07,100 --> 00:18:07,500
Plus,

520
00:18:07,500 --> 00:18:09,500
But what happens is, you've basically set the learning rate to zero.

521
00:18:09,500 --> 00:18:10,980
And just like that, the training process grinds to a halt.

522
00:18:10,980 --> 00:18:16,380
And it was precisely this flaw that led to the development of the next method, RMSprop.

523
00:18:16,380 --> 00:18:17,520
And then there are others like ADAM.

524
00:18:17,520 --> 00:18:20,160
At their core, they're all trying to improve the same thing.

525
00:18:22,820 --> 00:18:24,580
and only keep the influence of recent gradients.

526
00:18:24,580 --> 00:18:27,120
And that was the first optimization for adaptive learning rates.

527
00:18:27,120 --> 00:18:31,390
And RMSprop... well, that was after AlexNet ignited the deep learning boom back in 2012.

528
00:18:31,390 --> 00:18:33,730
This led to the development of deeper and deeper networks.

529
00:18:33,730 --> 00:18:35,050
and training took longer and longer.

530
00:18:35,050 --> 00:18:38,530
So basically, with these adaptive gradient methods, we just couldn't make progress with the training anymore.

531
00:18:38,530 --> 00:18:40,100
This would cause the learning rate to shrink to zero.

532
00:18:40,100 --> 00:18:41,980
So, here's an idea for an improvement.

533
00:18:41,980 --> 00:18:43,300
And that's actually the problem with RMSprop.

534
00:18:43,300 --> 00:18:44,440
The idea behind it is very simple.

535
00:18:44,440 --> 00:18:47,820
Instead of summing up the squares of all the gradients from the entire training process,

536
00:18:47,820 --> 00:18:50,310
Because that would just make the denominator larger and larger, right?

537
00:18:50,310 --> 00:18:51,570
the learning rate would eventually drop to zero.

538
00:18:51,570 --> 00:18:52,850
So, it doesn't use all of them anymore.

539
00:18:52,850 --> 00:18:55,450
Instead, it only uses the most recent ones, like the last ten updates, right?

540
00:18:55,450 --> 00:18:57,270
In this case, it stabilizes to a certain value.

541
00:18:57,270 --> 00:19:00,550
So, by using this one clever little trick,

542
00:19:00,550 --> 00:19:02,030
This solves the problem of the denominator getting infinitely large.

543
00:19:02,030 --> 00:19:04,230
and the problem of the learning rate shrinking to zero.

544
00:19:04,230 --> 00:19:05,070
And what's interesting is,

545
00:19:05,070 --> 00:19:08,039
Now, this optimization method is an old friend of ours.

546
00:19:08,039 --> 00:19:09,559
It was proposed by Hinton.

547
00:19:09,559 --> 00:19:11,319
But he didn't even write it up as a formal paper.

548
00:19:11,319 --> 00:19:13,830
Because he felt this improvement was just so logical.

549
00:19:13,830 --> 00:19:15,750
So he just mentioned it in an online course,

550
00:19:15,750 --> 00:19:18,630
After he wrote it down in his slides, it just took off and became the new standard.

551
00:19:18,630 --> 00:19:23,499
So, as a result, when people cited it, there was no proper paper to reference. This is how it ended up being cited.

552
00:19:23,499 --> 00:19:24,099
Right.

553
00:19:24,099 --> 00:19:25,659
In this section, we have this so-called 'COSER'...

554
00:19:25,659 --> 00:19:28,639
Just a single page from a lecture's PowerPoint.

555
00:19:28,639 --> 00:19:32,469
And just like that, the algorithm we just saw in the PPT became the new mainstream.

556
00:19:32,469 --> 00:19:33,749
Let's take a look at its formula.

557
00:19:33,749 --> 00:19:35,609
Now, this might look a lot more complicated than the last one.

558
00:19:35,609 --> 00:19:37,880
And that's really the biggest difference.

559
00:19:39,680 --> 00:19:41,660
So it's not the sum of all the squares, right?

560
00:19:41,660 --> 00:19:42,780
It's based on the most recent ones.

561
00:19:42,780 --> 00:19:46,320
So, what this does is, it prevents the learning rate from decaying all the way to zero.

562
00:19:46,320 --> 00:19:47,980
And on top of that, it also maintains its adaptability.

563
00:19:47,980 --> 00:19:50,940
So your recent gradients haven't plateaued either, right?

564
00:19:50,940 --> 00:19:51,880
And what about the previous ones?

565
00:19:51,880 --> 00:19:52,260
Right?

566
00:19:52,260 --> 00:19:55,120
And it's also particularly well-suited for non-stationary objectives.

567
00:19:55,120 --> 00:19:56,520
So, it's incredibly useful.

568
00:19:56,520 --> 00:19:58,540
However, it does have its limitations.

569
00:19:58,540 --> 00:20:00,500
First of all, it's just an adaptive learning rate.

570
00:20:00,500 --> 00:20:02,680
It doesn't take the gradient into account, right?

571
00:20:02,680 --> 00:20:04,040
For instance, which direction should it move in?

572
00:20:04,040 --> 00:20:04,600
It doesn't have that.

573
00:20:04,600 --> 00:20:06,360
So, this can also cause oscillations.

574
00:20:06,360 --> 00:20:07,600
And on top of that, there are these issues.

575
00:20:07,600 --> 00:20:10,130
Of course, it also adds another hyperparameter.

576
00:20:10,450 --> 00:20:12,250
So, despite these drawbacks,

577
00:20:12,250 --> 00:20:14,650
So, what it's actually doing is already happening during the training process.

578
00:20:14,650 --> 00:20:17,240
It became especially popular for things like RNNs.

579
00:20:17,240 --> 00:20:19,760
Especially when the loss landscape is quite rugged.

580
00:20:19,760 --> 00:20:20,580
It's incredibly effective.

581
00:20:20,580 --> 00:20:25,240
So, for a while, RMSprop became the go-to choice for training neural networks.

582
00:20:25,240 --> 00:20:26,160
the go-to choice.

583
00:20:26,160 --> 00:20:28,550
This was the case until ADAM appeared in 2015.

584
00:20:28,550 --> 00:20:31,030
So, what's the core idea behind ADAM?

585
00:20:31,030 --> 00:20:33,190
Then, around 2014 to 2015,

586
00:20:33,190 --> 00:20:36,590
By this point, two distinct schools of thought had clearly emerged in the field of deep learning optimization.

587
00:20:36,590 --> 00:20:39,370
One is the adaptive gradient approach.

588
00:20:39,370 --> 00:20:41,850
And then there's the other track, which is all about improving upon it, right?

589
00:20:41,850 --> 00:20:45,550
The idea is to let different parameters use different learning rates.

590
00:20:45,550 --> 00:20:49,290
Then there's another method, which is the momentum method, an idea that's been around since 1964.

591
00:20:49,290 --> 00:20:50,590
So, we just give it some momentum.

592
00:20:50,590 --> 00:20:52,700
Both of these methods are incredibly useful, by the way.

593
00:20:52,700 --> 00:20:54,040
So, since each has its own strengths,

594
00:20:54,040 --> 00:20:55,800
So, why not just combine them?

595
00:20:55,800 --> 00:20:57,780
And so, in 2014, it was born.

596
00:20:57,780 --> 00:21:01,080
ADAM is short for Adaptive Moment Estimation.

597
00:21:01,080 --> 00:21:01,600
Makes sense, right?

598
00:21:01,600 --> 00:21:03,000
I need both the direction,

599
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:03,860
and I also need the step size.

600
00:21:03,860 --> 00:21:07,160
So, that's basically the ADAM formula, which, you know, is just a whole bunch of math.

601
00:21:07,160 --> 00:21:10,240
And then, it also applies some bias correction to it.

602
00:21:10,240 --> 00:21:12,720
So, it doesn't really matter what value you initialize it with at the very beginning.

603
00:21:12,720 --> 00:21:13,720
It can adapt to all of them.

604
00:21:13,720 --> 00:21:16,820
So, that's why the first step makes perfect sense.

605
00:21:16,820 --> 00:21:18,460
And that's why it became so popular.

606
00:21:18,460 --> 00:21:19,780
It's just incredibly, incredibly useful.

607
00:21:19,780 --> 00:21:21,220
So, what are its three main advantages?

608
00:21:21,220 --> 00:21:22,860
First, it introduced the concept of momentum, right?

609
00:21:22,860 --> 00:21:24,800
And it can also reference past gradients.

610
00:21:24,800 --> 00:21:26,040
And the updates become much smoother.

611
00:21:26,040 --> 00:21:27,160
and it's less likely to get stuck.

612
00:21:27,160 --> 00:21:28,340
oscillations.

613
00:21:28,340 --> 00:21:30,580
Second, I also want to apply this to each individual parameter.

614
00:21:30,580 --> 00:21:33,480
In this case, we're still using a single learning rate for all the parameters.

615
00:21:33,480 --> 00:21:35,660
So now, I'm going to do something similar to RMSprop.

616
00:21:35,660 --> 00:21:37,320
for all the parameters.

617
00:21:37,320 --> 00:21:40,080
assign its own learning rate to each parameter.

618
00:21:40,080 --> 00:21:42,880
So, it basically combines the strengths of both.

619
00:21:42,880 --> 00:21:44,570
So you could say it's incredibly versatile.

620
00:21:44,570 --> 00:21:46,730
And for a very long time, it was pretty much the go-to choice.

621
00:21:46,730 --> 00:21:49,490
It became the default optimizer for pretty much all developers.

622
00:21:49,490 --> 00:21:54,720
But as people dug deeper, they found that the idea behind Adam was exceptionally good.

623
00:21:54,720 --> 00:21:56,740
But in reality, it had a hidden bug.

624
00:21:56,740 --> 00:21:59,080
This is actually an issue with weight decay.

625
00:21:59,080 --> 00:22:01,740
So, in the traditional stochastic gradient descent,

626
00:22:01,740 --> 00:22:03,320
that is, the decay of the weights.

627
00:22:03,320 --> 00:22:05,080
So, as the weights get smaller and smaller,

628
00:22:05,080 --> 00:22:07,640
In fact, it's pretty much equivalent to L2 regularization.

629
00:22:07,640 --> 00:22:09,780
So, in the early days, we had Adam.

630
00:22:09,780 --> 00:22:12,620
It also adds this L2 term to the gradient.

631
00:22:12,620 --> 00:22:14,220
But then, people started to run into a problem.

632
00:22:14,220 --> 00:22:18,800
The thing is, what this does is, it takes the regularization signal, which is supposed to be stable, right?

633
00:22:18,800 --> 00:22:20,500
The regularization signal itself should be stable.

634
00:22:20,500 --> 00:22:23,100
But what ended up happening was, it got scaled down along with everything else by the adaptive mechanism.

635
00:22:23,100 --> 00:22:27,220
This means the effect of regularization is being distorted from its original purpose by the adaptive mechanism.

636
00:22:27,220 --> 00:22:28,220
You can't do that.

637
00:22:28,220 --> 00:22:32,740
So basically, you can just think of it as a bug in how it handles the weights.

638
00:22:32,740 --> 00:22:34,380
This would cause the regularization to fail.

639
00:22:34,380 --> 00:22:37,980
So then, in 2017, Ilya Sutskever came up with a proposal.

640
00:22:37,980 --> 00:22:40,740
And the 'W' in AdamW? Well, that stands for 'weight'.

641
00:22:40,740 --> 00:22:45,010
Essentially, it just decouples the gradient update from the weight decay.

642
00:22:45,010 --> 00:22:47,420
So, the general formula would look something like this.

643
00:22:47,420 --> 00:22:49,580
But this actually introduces yet another hyperparameter.

644
00:22:49,580 --> 00:22:52,840
But the thing is, it solves the problem with Adam.

645
00:22:52,840 --> 00:22:55,480
So, it might seem like a very, very small improvement.

646
00:22:55,480 --> 00:22:56,840
But in the case of Transformers,

647
00:22:56,840 --> 00:22:57,520
BERT,

648
00:22:57,520 --> 00:22:59,000
and large language models like ViT,

649
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:00,800
It's pretty much the de facto standard.

650
00:23:00,800 --> 00:23:03,240
The vast majority of models we see today,

651
00:23:03,240 --> 00:23:04,570
They all use it at their core.

652
00:23:04,570 --> 00:23:06,470
And we're not at the grand finale yet.

653
00:23:06,470 --> 00:23:09,250
And then, more recently, around 2024, right?

654
00:23:09,250 --> 00:23:11,940
And then, people started to discover some new angles to tackle this problem.

655
00:23:11,940 --> 00:23:13,420
And that's where MIR comes in.

656
00:23:13,420 --> 00:23:15,120
So, what's its core idea?

657
00:23:15,120 --> 00:23:16,360
Basically, it's built on top of momentum.

658
00:23:16,360 --> 00:23:20,000
The core idea is to treat the parameters as a two-dimensional matrix.

659
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:21,100
and perform an orthogonal correction.

660
00:23:21,100 --> 00:23:23,830
It flattens out some of the singular values before taking another step.

661
00:23:23,830 --> 00:23:25,430
I know, that sounds super complicated, right?

662
00:23:25,430 --> 00:23:28,350
So, to put it simply, when it updates the parameters like this...

663
00:23:28,350 --> 00:23:30,290
the updates will all be in the same direction.

664
00:23:30,290 --> 00:23:33,410
This prevents it from moving off in a bunch of random directions.

665
00:23:33,410 --> 00:23:36,460
So, to put it simply, it's just really, really effective.

666
00:23:36,460 --> 00:23:37,580
For matrix-type data,

667
00:23:37,580 --> 00:23:39,060
But for biases, it's not really used.

668
00:23:39,060 --> 00:23:41,690
So, speaking of which, we also know about KIMI later on.

669
00:23:41,690 --> 00:23:43,390
In fact, KIMI also uses it.

670
00:23:43,390 --> 00:23:46,760
In fact, its efficiency is much higher than what you'd get with IMMW.

671
00:23:46,760 --> 00:23:49,080
So, when it comes to training the next generation of large models,

672
00:23:49,080 --> 00:23:51,020
Especially in all sorts of open-source models.

673
00:23:51,020 --> 00:23:53,590
In fact, it's still used quite a lot.

674
00:23:53,750 --> 00:23:56,070
So, this is pretty much the latest and greatest optimizer out there.

675
00:23:56,070 --> 00:23:56,830
So, to sum it all up,

676
00:23:56,830 --> 00:23:57,850
Our optimization journey,

677
00:23:57,850 --> 00:24:03,190
The driving force behind every single one of these advancements is really the same question: how can we make parameter updates faster and more stable?

678
00:24:03,190 --> 00:24:06,190
So, we'll start with the very original method: batch gradient descent.

679
00:24:06,190 --> 00:24:08,710
This established the fundamental conceptual framework.

680
00:24:08,710 --> 00:24:12,530
Basically, all the subsequent developments have been built upon this foundational idea.

681
00:24:12,530 --> 00:24:13,770
And then, we introduced stochasticity.

682
00:24:13,770 --> 00:24:15,850
So, 'stochastic' just means it uses a single sample.

683
00:24:15,850 --> 00:24:17,490
Now, this method is certainly faster, no doubt about it.

684
00:24:17,490 --> 00:24:19,159
But the problem is, it's way too noisy.

685
00:24:19,159 --> 00:24:20,959
So, we compromise with a mini-batch.

686
00:24:20,959 --> 00:24:21,759
So, instead of using just one,

687
00:24:21,759 --> 00:24:22,599
Let's use 32.

688
00:24:22,599 --> 00:24:24,030
or maybe 64 samples?

689
00:24:24,030 --> 00:24:25,510
This one is incredibly efficient.

690
00:24:25,510 --> 00:24:26,870
It's pretty much the default choice now.

691
00:24:26,870 --> 00:24:29,860
Then, we introduced another concept: momentum.

692
00:24:29,860 --> 00:24:33,120
This gives it some inertia to power through plateaus and small local minima.

693
00:24:33,120 --> 00:24:34,620
Then, later on, other researchers came along.

694
00:24:34,620 --> 00:24:37,720
The idea was that using a single learning rate for all the parameters wasn't a good fit.

695
00:24:37,720 --> 00:24:40,170
And so, this is where adaptive learning rates come into play.

696
00:24:40,170 --> 00:24:44,370
However, it had some minor issues that would cause the learning rate to decay to zero.

697
00:24:44,370 --> 00:24:47,130
So, to optimize it, RMSprop was introduced.

698
00:24:47,130 --> 00:24:49,100
This way, the learning rate won't drop to zero.

699
00:24:49,100 --> 00:24:53,580
Then came ADAM, which combined these optimizations for both momentum and the learning rate.

700
00:24:55,040 --> 00:24:56,960
And then came this one, which was incredibly effective.

701
00:24:56,960 --> 00:25:02,070
So, AdamW, well, it's basically a fix for the weight decay issue in the original Adam.

702
00:25:02,070 --> 00:25:03,910
and became the de facto standard.

703
00:25:03,910 --> 00:25:06,390
And then, starting from 2024,

704
00:25:06,390 --> 00:25:10,900
So, MIR works by considering the update direction as orthogonal to the weight matrix.

705
00:25:10,900 --> 00:25:12,880
This makes the update direction more stable.

706
00:25:12,880 --> 00:25:16,330
So, we're seeing it being used more and more in 2024.

707
00:25:16,330 --> 00:25:18,850
So, this is basically how you use an optimizer.

708
00:25:18,850 --> 00:25:23,020
So, in our day-to-day work with all sorts of machine learning tasks,

709
00:25:23,020 --> 00:25:24,620
In fact, this one is the most widely used.

710
00:25:24,620 --> 00:25:27,060
And another one that's actually used quite a lot is Adam.

711
00:25:27,060 --> 00:25:29,880
But in reality, different fields will have different preferences.

712
00:25:29,880 --> 00:25:31,920
It's not like there's a single, definitive answer.

713
00:25:31,920 --> 00:25:33,500
For instance, in many computer vision tasks,

714
00:25:33,500 --> 00:25:35,560
particularly on convolutional neural networks.

715
00:25:35,560 --> 00:25:37,650
SGD, in combination with momentum,

716
00:25:37,650 --> 00:25:40,330
But if we manage to tune the learning rate really well,

717
00:25:40,330 --> 00:25:43,010
its final accuracy can often still be optimized.

718
00:25:43,010 --> 00:25:44,510
it can even outperform Adam.

719
00:25:44,510 --> 00:25:47,730
For a long time, the go-to choice for large NLP models has been AdamW.

720
00:25:47,730 --> 00:25:50,699
But now, in 2024, Muon is making a comeback.

721
00:25:50,699 --> 00:25:53,339
So, when we're doing some quick experiments and prototyping,

722
00:25:53,339 --> 00:25:54,599
ADAM is the fastest of the fast.

723
00:25:54,599 --> 00:25:57,270
You can often get a pretty good baseline just by using it.

724
00:25:57,270 --> 00:26:00,680
In cases with sparse data, or during short online cycles,

725
00:26:00,680 --> 00:26:03,540
So, the adaptive learning rate is still a really useful method.

726
00:26:03,540 --> 00:26:07,590
So, for things like ad CTR prediction, these traditional LP methods also have some real-world value.

